{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"31a86af7-a54a-49ba-811b-37cf99064b51","content":"There are two reliable approaches — both read the source of truth directly from your installed SDK rather than guessing.\n\n---\n\n### Option 1: Inspect the workload pack's MSBuild props (fastest)\n\n```bash\n# Find your SDK root\nDOTNET_ROOT=$(dotnet --info | grep \"Base Path\" | awk '{print $3}' | sed 's|/sdk/.*||')\n\n# Find the Android SDK workload pack and grep for version properties\ngrep -rh \\\n  \"AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion\\|CommandLineToolsVersion\\|PlatformToolsVersion\\|compileSdkVersion\\|targetSdkVersion\" \\\n  \"$DOTNET_ROOT/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.\"* \\\n  --include=\"*.props\" --include=\"*.targets\"\n```\n\nThe pack at `$DOTNET_ROOT/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.<rid>/<version>/tools/` contains `.props`/`.targets` files that define the exact versions the build system expects (e.g., `AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion`, `JavaSdkVersion`, etc.).\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: Resolve via MSBuild (most complete)\n\nCreate a throwaway project and ask MSBuild to resolve everything:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new android -n SdkProbe --no-restore\ncd SdkProbe\n\n# Dump the resolved Android SDK properties\ndotnet msbuild SdkProbe.csproj \\\n  -getProperty:AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion \\\n  -getProperty:AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion \\\n  -getProperty:TargetPlatformVersion \\\n  -getProperty:JavaSdkVersion \\\n  -getProperty:AndroidNdkVersion\n\ncd .. && rm -rf SdkProbe\n```\n\nThis returns the **exact** values your SDK will use at build time. In CI, translate these to `sdkmanager` package names:\n\n```bash\n# Example mapping from resolved properties:\n#   AndroidSdkBuildToolsVersion=34.0.0  →  \"build-tools;34.0.0\"\n#   TargetPlatformVersion=34            →  \"platforms;android-34\"\n#   AndroidCommandLineToolsVersion=11.0 →  \"cmdline-tools;11.0\"\n\nsdkmanager --install \\\n  \"build-tools;${BUILD_TOOLS_VER}\" \\\n  \"platforms;android-${API_LEVEL}\" \\\n  \"cmdline-tools;${CMDLINE_VER}\" \\\n  \"platform-tools\"\n```\n\n---\n\n**Option 2 is the most CI-friendly** — it's a single `dotnet msbuild -getProperty` call that works regardless of SDK version or host OS, and it reflects any `Directory.Build.props` overrides in your repo.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e75ba2b1-81bd-4f7e-9c2a-22a7d48075a2","outputTokens":675,"requestId":"9423:56792:15510E9:17C08CD:6A067227"},"id":"2eab6eba-a4c1-4dcd-a25d-b1f995c2fc9d","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:09:09.428Z","parentId":"2377192f-ea3e-44e8-a9f4-31c1704aa09a"}
